Some two hundred and fifty years ago\'85\par

\pard\widctlpar\fi660\sl276\slmult1\i0\par

\pard\widctlpar\sl276\slmult1 The banging on the gates grew louder, screams of soldiers that had been eating like pigs for days.\par

\pard\widctlpar\fi660\sl276\slmult1\ldblquote They\rquote re breaking through, your Grace!\rdblquote  Aleksandr shouted.\par
Magdalena lifted a broadsword from the wall. Her father\rquote s broadsword.\par
It was as good a weapon as any to die holding.\par
\ldblquote I had always said, hadn\rquote t I? That it wouldn\rquote t be the undead that killed us, but the vultures who come to pick at the scraps.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Have you finished the evacuation?\rdblquote  she said, looking at how the torchlight glinted from the reflection, her face in the polished hilt.\par
\ldblquote If you can call it that,\rdblquote  Aleksandr said. \ldblquote Ten people. Two years ago we had thousands.\rdblquote  He was fighting back tears.\par
Magdalena put a hand on her friend\rquote s shoulder. \ldblquote We did everything we could. This wasn\rquote t our fault.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Tell that to my brother, wandering around outside, mumbling about brains.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Make sure you don\rquote t join him. Go. Follow the party out.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote\'85 You say that like you\rquote re not coming.\rdblquote\par
Magdalena paused at the door. \ldblquote You seem to have forgotten. For today, I\rquote m still the queen. Captain goes down with the ship, darling.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Magda!\rdblquote  he shouted, but she was already gone.\par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\sl276\slmult1\qc #\par

\pard\widctlpar\fi660\sl276\slmult1\par

\pard\widctlpar\sl276\slmult1 Her heart pounded in her chest as she climbed the ladder onto the parapets, her boots catching on the rungs. The gate was all but splinters now, but it only needed to hold for another minute or so.\par

\pard\widctlpar\fi660\sl276\slmult1 She grabbed a torch from the wall. \ldblquote Parasites!\rdblquote  she shouted over the crowd. \ldblquote Hear me now!\rdblquote\par
Down the other side of the wall, thirty men in mail rammed the gates with battering rams.\par
A few years ago, it would\rquote ve been suicide for them. Now, they were coming to claim an empty house.\par
A few spectators up the back spotted her, and pointed. \ldblquote There she is!\rdblquote\par
She tried to stand in the most commanding stance she had, but she\rquote d never been a war general. \ldblquote You\rquote ve watched our country suffer, let us turn on one another rather than help! You let the undead plague grow to fill your coffers! So I give you one warning! You wanted this castle, you\rquote ll pay for it with your blood!\rdblquote\par
And she dropped the torch over the edge.\par
It hit oil. Or gunpowder. Something, a magic in the grounds that had been there since before she was born, took. The flames ran around the edge of the castle, and then began to climb. A pentagram of flame engulfed the structure.\par
Magda raised her arms into the air, watching the smoke rise into the air like incense. The heat was like a wall, and she smiled as the assailants started to scream, their skin bubbling and crackling like kindling.\par
\ldblquote Even God wouldn\rquote t want your souls!\rdblquote  she shouted, inhaling smoke.  There would be nothing left but ash.\par
She screamed, as she started to burn.\par
\par

