\pard\widctlpar\sl276\slmult1\ldblquote You\rquote re not allowed to sleep here, young lady,\rdblquote  the old librarian man said. \ldblquote I\rquote m sorry, you\rquote re going to have to go to the church.\rdblquote\par

\pard\widctlpar\fi660\sl276\slmult1 Magda was lying bundled in a cloak in a chair in the corner, but she bolted up in fear at the voice. \ldblquote No. Not the church. I can\rquote t.\rdblquote  She\rquote d been travelling for days, and even these vampire limbs were exhausted.\par
\ldblquote Whatever you\rquote ve done, I\rquote m sure the priest will overlook it.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s not what I\rquote ve done\'85\rdblquote  she said.\par
The old man sat down on the recliner next to her. \ldblquote I know how it feels to not have the blessing of the church.\rdblquote\par
She gulped, curled herself up tighter. She\rquote d never been afraid to die, until now. Fear sat uncomfortably on her like a new lover.\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t know who I am now.\rdblquote\par
He nodded, sagely despite the lack of context.\par
\ldblquote Please,\rdblquote  she said.\par
He sighed, before relenting. \ldblquote One night.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Thank you.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Maybe read a book,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote It\rquote ll at least look like you\rquote re supposed to be here. Besides, it always makes \i me\i0  feel like I belong.\rdblquote  He lay back in his recliner, and began to doze.\par
\par

